segments.text: Our organization escorted the paratroopers in and the gliders.
Was this the evening before D-Day?
No, it wasn't.
Or was it at the same time?
Same time, on D-Day.
On D-Day, when the gliders went in, we were escorting the ships towing the gliders.
The paratroopers went in.
I think land first, and then the gliders came in.
And did you help plan where they were going to land?
Yeah.
Well, not where they were going to land.
No, I was only planning our escort, giving them, planning the times.
We flew by squadrons, and we had squadrons taking off at that time to rendezvous with one of the, each one of the trains of gliders.
Were you upset that you weren't going to be in?
I was very upset that I wasn't participating, but they said that everybody that knew what the plans were, none of us could fly on that day.
I did fly the next day.
Now when you flew the next day, what was your mission?
We were supporting the troops on the ground.
We were given either targets or we were ported in to the ground controller that he directed us.
And that's what we did the rest of the work.
And we covered that until the breakthrough.
And we covered Patton all the way across.
So you worked directly with Third Army?
Yeah.
We had to fill our wing tanks with maps and take them up there and drop them.
If Patton would liberate one of the German Army's warehouses, he'd send us a truckload of booze of some type.
He'd send us Cointreau.
We'd have free Cointreau at the bar.
Later on, we liberated the champagne caves.
We had free champagne at the bar.
I think we sold a nickel a bottle or something like that.
And if he got in Germany, he'd be with the snobs.
He was very, very well thought of by us in what he was doing.
And he didn't forget who was helping him either.
I was wondering about when you flew across the channel on the day after D-Day, D-plus-1, you must have seen, what were your impressions when you saw it?
Oh, it was exciting.
And all of the ships were out there in the harbor.
It was just exciting.
It really made you feel a lot of pride in what we were doing.
wanted to get on with.
We were really excited.
And we were one of the first units to get transferred over into.
That was going to be my next question.
Where were you transferred in France?
We went to Pont Tarzan, which is right at the base of the Brittany Peninsula, right down the road from Mont Saint-Michel.
a very famous tourist place there based in Britain.
How were the conditions?
Well, we had a pure steel plant runway that the engineers had built.
We had an old chateau where there
group headquarters was.
We had some barracks for the men that the Germans had been using.
We had our men sleep there.
It was so much better accommodations than we had in England where we were living in tents.
We thought it was good.
How'd the French people treat you?
Were they happy to see you?
Oh, I'll say.
They were really number one.
Boy, they couldn't do enough for us.
They were really excited.
They told stories of how the Germans had been bailing out of this barracks that they had, jumping out of the second story.
They were very emotional.
Extremely.
They couldn't, they just couldn't do enough for us.
What did they do for you?
I mean, did they give you food or wine or anything?
Oh, they, they gave us, you know, they'd give you food and wine if you wanted.
If we had food, we went to the Moe Sammy Shell and we'd have a 12 course dinner with wine.
Sometimes we had to furnish part of the food, though, like meat or something like that.
We had everything there.
We had chicken, eggs.
I remember Madame Foulard, a very famous eating establishment.
Madame Foulard and Tom, they were all famous.
We thought we were doing pretty high time.
And how often did you fly a mission whenever the Army needed your assistance?
Yes, we had Frag orders that came in.
It was fairly often.
Were you involved after the breakout, were you involved in supporting the liberation of Paris?
Or were you moving?
Yes.
We were indirectly involved because we were bombing, and we leapfrogged up and back near there.
And it so happens that one of our men, who was the best man at my wedding, by the way, a close friend of mine, was shot down on one of these ground support missions.
And he was in Paris after the
As they were liberating Paris, a general had left and left his colonel in charge, and the colonel surrendered to my captain, Pete Carson.
Surrendered the city to him.
And he said that was really exciting.
It really whined at that.
He finally made his way back to where we were.
I noticed that in October of 1944, just a few months after the invasion, you became the commander of the 365th Fighter Squadron.
Yes.
Were you promoted at that time?
Well, I went over as a first lieutenant, and I was later promoted to captain.
I was an operations officer for a flight commander, and then I was an operations officer.
Then I was made squadron commander.
I was promoted to major.
Yeah, you were promoted November 1, 1944 to major.
And I was made squadron commander of another squadron.
We had gotten a new group commander by that time.
He really influenced me a lot.
Well, we had a, who was it?
James B. Tipton.
He retired late at night.
We had a guy in charge, Cecil Wells, a group commander.
During the time we trained, when we went over, and he got shot down.
But he was too conservative in our community.
He was what we called a grandma.
A grandma?
Yeah.
He was always afraid that we were going to do something, taking these boys over, and he wanted to bring every damn one of them back.
He just was too conservative and wouldn't let us be aggressive.
And we got this guy Tipton in.
He showed me how to turn an organization around, how to raise morale, how to get a spree to court.
We painted the tails of our airplanes orange.
And we got word later on that the Germans knew when they saw the orange tails, they all ran for cover because they knew we were going to get to hell.
beat on it.
And we compiled a in the Oval Record after this guy joined us.
We just turned the whole organization.
Was he a general?
No, he was a colonel.
But he was your colonel and you were the major under him.
Yeah.
Was morale low under this earlier man?
He wasn't low.
We were frustrated, more frustrated, because he didn't let us go.
He was too protective.
This guy just turned the whole organization around, and we got three presidential citations.
Did cash OPs also increase?
We had plenty of casualties anyway.
It was no great deal.
Well, we were fortunate, too, but when the Germans had passed on
We had the lousy weather and it was gruesome the first day we did take off.
Unfortunately, three squadrons of us got up there and one squadron just ran into all kinds of enemy aircraft and shot a bunch of them down and our squadron didn't even see one.
But we got up there, and we got comments back later about how appreciative they were when we got up there.
And we did, even though the weather was loud.
We couldn't really see the ground, but we were overhead.
And later on, after the weather cleared up, we did the job on five minutes straight.
And did you knock out the major target was probably the German tanks?
Yes, tanks.
We had rockets for tanks.
Did you knock some of those out just now?
Oh, yeah.
We disabled them at least.
We knocked them out completely.
What were your feelings when you did disable a tank?
It was a feeling of relation, and you couldn't wait to get back to talk about it.
That's sort of doing your job.
Well, that was sort of characteristic of fighter pilots, to get up early and get briefed and get off and get off on the mission.
And at that time, we would turn them around, maybe three missions a day.
No kidding.
During the, as it cleared up, as far as the Battle of the Bulge, the airplanes would go up for three missions a day.
The fighters, what, one mission a day, or the fighters?
Sometimes the pilots would go up for more than once.
Sometimes two missions a day.
Of course, the...
A lot depended on the weather and what was going on and what the ground forces needed.
And did you feel threatened by the Battle of the Bulge?
We all felt threatened by the Battle of the Bulge, yes.
But we didn't think it was going towe didn't think that they would be able to stop us.
That would only be temporary.
Yeah, which it was.
Sure.
Absolutely.
Now, when you became the commander of the fighter squadron, how many planes did you have under your control?
We had 25.
You personally had 25?
Yeah.
And how many pilots?
We had about 30 pilots.
How many maintenance personnel?
About a hundred.
About a hundred?
What were your feelings when you received, this is your first command, is that not right?
Well, the first overall command, yes.
And what were your feelings?
I was proud, very proud, and very eager to do the best I could.
take care of my men and get them in the air.
Were there major challenges?
Or was this pretty much carrying on?
What were your predecessors left off?
Or did you have to make some changes?
We had to make some changes because we were in a moving situation.
We had to improvise and we scrounged stuff and built ourselves a

operations building and then moved in boarded up all our tents so the man had a better place to live it was really a scrounging job to get things for your people and did you like the role of leadership
I guess I enjoyed it very much.
I looked at it as a challenge to see if I could inspire my people to do better and instill in them a spirit
cooperation, esprit de corps, want to get the job done.
Do you think you accomplished that?
I think I did.
I think we had as good a squadron as we rode over.
What type of airplanes did you have?
You still had the 47, so the whole time.
What was your opinion on the 47?
We loved the P-47.
It was a great airplane.
You can't imagine the things that we went through when we came back.
One boy had a cylinder shot off the top of it, lost all his oil, and threw all of it back.
That's durability.
And one of my airplanes, the one that I had my name on, everybody had his own airplane.
He didn't get to fly it.
unless it was ready when he came up with the schedule for his mission.
If it was ready, well, he took it.
One of my friends from Texas, Bryce Littlejohn from Marshall, had my airplane one day and an FW-190 or a Focke-Wulf 190 or an ME-109 or one of the others got on his tail and put 108 bullet holes
This airplane was mine.
But he got it back.
No kidding, didn't he?
He got a piece of equipment.
Yeah.
It was a real workhorse.
It was a real sturdy, sturdily built airplane.
It could take a punch.
It had an armored seat.
Eight machine guns.
It could carry three 1,000-pound bombs.

I was also wondering, when you became the commander, did this mean that you still got to go out on the missions, or did this reduce the number of missions you went on and increase the amount of administrative work?
It increased the amount of administrative work tremendously, but I still tried to fly regularly.
Probably not every day, but every other day or so.
I had 122 missions, I think.
You didn't have 122 missions?
Were there any differences when you moved from fighting in France to Germany?
Well, when we moved into Germany, we moved into an old Luftwaffe base, and we had fine quarters for our men.
Where'd you move?
You moved from this French base up in Brittany to, your next move then was into German, into the Luftwaffe base?
We moved, we spent the winter at this one near Nancy, and then our next move was into Germany.
Where?
My memory's bad.
Well, we can fill that in later.
OK.
Describe the base for me.
It was an old Luftwaffe base.
It had big pillows with swat stickers on it going inside.
It had nice big barracks and a good runway.
They didn't destroy it?
Why not?
They may have destroyed a few things on it.
They didn't ruin the runway?
They got out too quickly.
They hadn't moved in too quickly.
They really did.
Now, of course, when you'd come back and land, you'd land back in Germany.
Did you ever have any dealings during the war time with the German people?
Not really.
Not until after the war.
Okay.
Okay.
You continued through the end of the war then, right down to April, May 1945, to get support to the Third Army.
Yeah.
That was your primary mission then?
Well, no.
No, that's not true.
Oh, okay.
Then what was?
The 7th Army came up from the south.
And after the 7th Army came up, then we were transferred to the 19th Tactical Air Command and the 9th Tactical Air Command.
And we covered the 7th Army from then on.
We covered the 7th Army and then from then on came the war.
Were there any differences in working the 3rd versus the 7th?
Well, the 7th didn't have all the tanks and armor, although they had some.
Sure.
But until the winter was over, we were pretty well stagnated, it seemed to me.
They weren't moving much.
We waited until the spring and moved out.
Our relationship with them were very good.
Did they supply you like that?
Did they try to keep you around?
Well, no, they didn't do that, but they did visit us.
And we worked with him.
We sent forward air controllers up to work with him.
We had that direct association through our pilots.
They would go up to the ground controllers with riding tanks with them and direct the aircraft in to the targets.
April of 1945, you changed jobs, and you became the air inspector.
Is that right?
At the 64th Fighter Wing.
Why?
Why'd they change you from combat duty to an inspector position?
Well, combat was over.
Basically.
Basically over.
Well, it was over before I left.
They figured the group would be going home.
I wanted to stay, so I took this job to the golf course.
You wanted to stay on.
You had made up your mind that you did not want to go back to the United States, even though... No, I wanted to go into the city.
Okay, that's just the next question.
And I had made arrangements with this wing who said they were going, and I wanted to go with them.
I was picked off the 64th.
The 12th Tactical Air Command?
I thought they were gone?
No, there was another one.
It was a medium bomber.
I was picked off the 64th, and then the 12th Tactical, the boss of the 64th, pulled me out of there.
and put me in the Air Inspector's job.
And then they had a colonel come in and he came in and they put him over me, so I was an assistant Air Inspector.
Did you like the job of being an inspector?
I didn't particularly relish the job of being an inspector, but I did learn a lot.
I learned a whole lot as an inspector.
About what?
About administration.
of different modes of the Air Force.
And I got ideas from other people on how to do things.
And gave them some, too.
How to get the job done.
Yes.
What were the problems in Germany right as soon as the war ended, as far as the Air Force was concerned?
Well, number one problem was BD.
Yeah, I would imagine.
How'd you try to resolve those?
Well, it was made a command function to resolve them.
And what did you do to try to, I mean, what actions did you take?
You mean as the air inspector?
Yeah.
Well, we brought the problems to the attention of the command.
And they took it from there.
We took over the air drone at Swineford.
And that's where I started working in the journey.
Before we started working with the Germans, during this time did you also work with the Russians?
No.
I never saw a Russian.
You never saw a Russian?
Did you ever hear any stories about the Russians?
Or did you ever have any feelings toward the Russians one way or the other?
Well, I felt that I strongly feel that Mr. Roosevelt
He gave away the fact that, I mean, he gave away the option of us going and being into Berlin first, which we would be.
I think he gave that away to Mr. Stalin.
And we were damn mad about it.
All of us.
Because you wanted to continue on into Berlin?
I wanted to continue on into Berlin, and we wanted to...
We wanted to get as much of Germany as we could before the Russians got there.
Well, they were our allies at the time, much as they were.
Why did you want to commit your troops and take on the possibility of more American bloodshed if they were going to be our allies?
Well, we didn't think that we were going to be more American, much more than any bloodshed, or if any.
We think that it was all political.
We did not like the Russians.
You didn't like the Russians even before the war was over?
Even before the war was over, because of communism.
But you didn't work with any Russians yourself?
No.
This is just the general feeling.
The general feeling.
OK.
What was your mission as the commander of the 86th Fighter Group?
You said you started working with the Germans.
In what way?
Well, no, we worked with the local Germans.
Okay.
Burgermeisters and stuff.
We had to coordinate the supplies and stuff.
assist in getting themselves back on their own feet and taking care of themselves.
We had a mission of flying and making our presence known.
We flew regularly all over just to let them know that we were there.
And we stayed prepared to it.
to fight, too.

And if anything happened, we would have worked with the Army, who had taken over the, who had these political officers, I guess you'd call them, that took over the supervision of the government of the Burgermeister.
And we had a liaison with them.
And then we, of course, had this air base.
We had some of the German people there that worked there and continued working.
And we had some displaced persons.
They may have been Russians or they may have been Poles.
I don't know what they were that we had to send back.
Well, we used them as civilian employees on the base.
We fed them, housed them.
Did you eventually have to send them back?
We turned them over to the Army.
I don't know what they did.
How did you get along with the conquered enemy?
We didn't have any problems.
No problems with the Germans?
No.
Except we had problems with BD.
What were the feelings toward the Germans?
Well, we weren't particularly hostile.
We thought they were a victim of hit and run.
And I can remember when I first went with the 12th Tactical Air Command, my friend and I moved into a doctor's house.
He left everything there.
We just went in.
We never saw him.
It didn't last long, but it was quite nice.
And our quarters at Swineford were very good, too.
Of course, that place had been beaten up.
We had bombed that several times, but we put in our own runway.
There was still a plank runway.
Some of the barracks were undamaged and used then.
When you heard that the United States dropped the atomic bomb and that the war in the Pacific was over, how did you feel about that?
Well, I was glad to hear it was over.
I think we all were.
It was a relief, too.
Yet at the same time, now you wouldn't be able to have more combat missions.
Well, that wasn't going to bother me.
It was over.
That's not to say that I want to go out and apply combat.
Just apply combat.
I don't.
It's scary.
It's not...
It's not...
I think it's hazardous to your health.
Yeah, that's right.
It's surgeon general, like I said.
I got shot up, I guess, at least 15 times.
You did?
Yeah.
Shot down once, but shot up.
Do you consider yourself lucky?
Very lucky.
Extremely lucky.
Were you, besides your nose,
During this time, 1945 to 1947, America's armed forces dwindled from 12 million down to a million and a half.
Rapid demobilization.
Explosive demobilization, I'd say.
That was the situation in Germany.
The rail was low, and people had lots of points.
He had morale problems like what I did.
Farmed a football team.
A classmate of mine at this point now that coaches.
We won the USA championship.
No kidding.
We had a lot of fun.
So in other words, you directed sporting events.
Yeah.
Well, we had other things too.
We got him the permission to go deer hunting.
Really?
Yeah.
We shot a lot of deer.
Where'd they go?
They went in the woods.
There were lots of woods in town.
Oh, yeah.
And lots of deer.
We enjoyed venison, too.
For officers and men?
Yeah.
Did you set up an officer's club and EM club?
Oh, yes.
They had nice... And they also had Red Cross clubs.
Did you try to bring in movies or movie stars?
We had movies.
And then we started there.
We had B.B.
Daniels at the Pond Tarsen right after B.
Day.
We had Spike Jones stayed with us at Pond Tarsen for just a couple of weeks.
And they went out to the various Army units.
Of course, we were Army too then.
And played for them and played for us at our club.
And they stood in.
We set up an officer's club and an enlisted man's club everywhere we went.
We did it with a tent.
As far as... Good for morale.
Sure.
And did you actually feel that you increased more?
Yes.
We had hires for you in our organization, Michael.
Very much.
All your friends and a lot of the associates and a lot of pilots
back into civilian life.
At any time did you feel that you wanted to go back into civilian life?
None whatsoever.
As a matter of fact, my father offered me the opportunity.
He said before he wanted me to come in the business with me and my brother.
He said, no, I want to stay in the airport.
Thought I found a career.
I enjoyed flying.
I don't understand it.
I thought it was an opportunity.
It gave me an opportunity as a major to have a colonel's job.
And I was on the list to be promoted to lieutenant colonel when the war ended.
No, they didn't.
No, they realized demobilization, they wouldn't need that many officers.
Okay, so through 1946, until 1946, you were the deputy commander of 64th Fighter Wing?
Well, that was a consolidation.
It looks like it.
It was a consolidation of the Fighter Wing and the group.
And they just moved the Fighter Wing, which looked at a
a town near there that moved them out there to the air base.
And the wing ran the group, I mean ran the organization there, and also all the other fighter planes that were under.
So it was just a... Well, there was a lot of consolidation at this time.
They sent the 86 fighter group home.
and the people that were eligible to go, went.
The rest of the regular officers that were there stayed, and the others that didn't have enough points to go.
In 1946, though, you have a rather unusual assignment, which lasts from May 46 to September 47, and that's that the officers
I was a master of the sword.
Oh, what's a master of the sword?
It's the physical education department.
And what did you do there?
This is kind of an unusual assignment for a fighter pilot.
It wasn't the Air Force then, I was in the Army still.
Yeah, sure, still the Army Air Corps.
And West Point had pretty high priority on selecting who they wanted for instructors.
And I was selected by the Director of Physical Education, if you will, or the Master of the Sword, to come there and be a...
What I did, I came home on R&R expecting to go back to Germany and get a good job in the 64th Fighter Wing.
But while I was home on R&R, my orders were changed and I was sent to West Point to be an instructor.
What were your feelings about that?
I was highly pissed off.
I wanted to be, I got married, and I wanted to be the first guy back to Germany with his wife.
And my classmate, one of my classmates did just that.
He was the first guy to have his wife over there.
Because by this time, the Army allowed people to have dependents.
Yeah.
But you could still have her at West Point.
Oh, I did.
Two of our children were born there.
And she enjoyed wrestling.
And I did enjoy it, too.
But I did not want to get out of flying airplanes.
And did you like instructing cadets?
I enjoyed them.
And physical education.
Yeah, I know.
But what type?
I mean, what did you?
Well, I taught wrestling.
Wrestling.
And I was on the wrestling team.
I taught wrestling.
I taught administration of athletic programs.
I taught football coaching.
I taught calisthenics.
Why do you have an engineer teaching this?
I wasn't an engineer.
Well, true, you were an army officer, but you had an engineering background and a mathematical background.
They select the instructors up there based on their records.
I had played football and I coached football there in my last year as one of the coaches there.
I played lacrosse and I played a lot of sports and of course the wrestling team.
this was the type of person that he wanted.
Now, is there any tension between the returning veterans, combat hardened veterans, and the new cadets who are just starting out at West Point?
Any tension, or do they look up to you, or, you know, this is a peculiar time?
No, because they had in the, they had in the, in the, in the Corps, they had guys that had
had combat.
And they were in the Corps.
And they were looked up to.
They really were.
So they had individual people who had been enlisted men then who had gone to Europe and now they, after combat they had, they received appointments to West Point to start.
Some of them had been, even one guy had been a captain.
No kidding.
And a pilot.
Mm-hmm.
But in the reserve.
And then when he was commissioned, what did they commission him as?
He had already been commissioned, so what did they commission him?
He resigned that commission.
He resigned the commission to go to... Well, he doesn't have to resign his reserve commission.
He goes in as a vet.
He still is a reserve captain.
That's a peculiar situation.
Yeah, it was a peculiar situation.
They looked up to him.
Yeah, they really did.
During this time, of course, there was an attempt, which was successful, to separate the Army Air Corps from the Army and make it the Air Force.
What were your feelings on this?
I was elated.
Why?
I wanted to be separate from the Army.
Well, you were a West Point graduate.
That had nothing to do with it, in terms of air power.
Because air power was subordinated to people who didn't know enough about it.
And they proved that when they made the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
Even during the war, the head of the Air Corps was made General of the Air Force, General Arnold.

The three separate services, in my opinion, the Air Force should not be subordinated to the Army, because it goes beyond the Army, where the Army is not even involved in strategic bombing and so forth.
So all of us that were in the Air Corps,
Happy to serve in the Air Force.
You just wanted your independence.
And commanding and being under command yourself.
Yeah, and being under commanders.
Who were Air Corps people.
Air Corps people and not Army.
You were teaching at West Point at the time with a lot of Army officers who were not Air Corps types.
What were the feelings toward this?
